SIMPLE: embrasure
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Embrasure
<hw>Em*bra"sure</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Embrace</er>.]</ety> <def>An embrace.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧Our locked <xex>embrasures</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Embrasure</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Embrasure
<hw>Em*bra"sure</hw> <pr>(277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr.
<ets>embraser</ets>, perh. equiv. to <ets>⟦eacute⟧braser</ets> to widen
an opening; of unknown origin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>
<def>A splay of a door or window.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Apart, in the twilight gloom of a window's
<qex>embrasure</qex>,⟦br⟧
Sat the lovers.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>An aperture with slant sides in a
wall or parapet, through which cannon are pointed and discharged; a
crenelle. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Casemate</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Embrave</ent>⟦br⟧
